<task id="AIPU2-110" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Safety perimeter end-to-end test</title>
    <phase>6</phase>
    <tags>testing, ai-safety</tags>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-065, AIPU2-090</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Validate the complete safety perimeter end-to-end: prompt injection blocking, groundedness
    annotation, citation verification, and privilege filtering. This test suite covers the four
    safety capabilities implemented in Phase 3 (AIPU2-065) and the UI annotation layer
    (AIPU2-090). These are not unit tests of individual services — they are integration tests
    that exercise the full path from SSE request to annotated response, verifying that safety
    checks fire correctly and that unsafe outputs are either blocked or annotated before
    reaching the user.
  </prompt>
  <role>QA or security-focused test developer with knowledge of the AI safety pipeline.</role>
  <goal>
    An automated (or scripted manual) test suite covers all four safety perimeter capabilities.
    All prompt injection payloads are blocked. All ungrounded claims are annotated. All citation
    verification badge states (valid, invalid, partial) render correctly. Privilege filter
    prevents cross-matter content. Results are documented in a test report.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r2/design.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Safety</file>
      <file>src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/SafetyAnnotations</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Compile a prompt injection test payload library: at least 5 direct injection payloads (e.g. "Ignore previous instructions and...") and 3 indirect injections embedded in document content. Use Azure Content Safety PromptShield test vectors where available.</step>
    <step>Test direct prompt injection: send each payload via the SSE chat endpoint, verify HTTP 400 or safety-blocked SSE event is returned, verify no AI response is generated.</step>
    <step>Test indirect prompt injection: upload a document containing injection text, ask the AI to summarize it, verify the injection is neutralized and the summary does not follow injected instructions.</step>
    <step>Test groundedness annotation: send a query where the AI is likely to produce an ungrounded claim (no supporting document loaded), verify the response includes a groundedness annotation badge (ungrounded state) on the relevant claim.</step>
    <step>Test citation verification: (a) valid citation — verify green badge; (b) invalid citation (hallucinated source) — verify red badge; (c) partial citation (document exists but text not found) — verify amber badge. Use controlled test documents.</step>
    <step>Test privilege filter: create two matter contexts (Matter A, Matter B). Load documents in Matter A, switch context to Matter B without loading new documents, send a query. Verify AI does not reference Matter A content, and a privilege boundary notification appears in the UI.</step>
    <step>Document all test cases, payloads, expected results, and actual results in notes/safety-e2e-test-report.md.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>All 5+ direct prompt injection payloads return a blocked response — no AI-generated text reaches the client.</criterion>
    <criterion>All 3 indirect injection payloads are neutralized — AI summary does not execute injected instructions.</criterion>
    <criterion>Ungrounded claims are annotated with an ungrounded groundedness badge in the UI.</criterion>
    <criterion>Valid citations show green badge, invalid citations show red badge, partial citations show amber badge.</criterion>
    <criterion>Cross-matter query returns no privileged content from the previous matter and shows a privilege boundary notification.</criterion>
    <criterion>Test report is written to notes/safety-e2e-test-report.md with all payloads, results, and pass/fail verdicts.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
